<seg id=1> Bosnian Serbs Hope To Negotiate New Peace Initiative </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> XINHUA NEWS AGENCY WIRE Belgrade, Aug. 31 (Wang Sen reporting): Momcilo Krajisnik, speaker of parliament for Bosnia's "Republic of Serbia", stressed on "Voice of Serbia" today that with the people's rejection in a referendum of the International Contact Group's proposed territorial divisions in Bosnia and Herzegovina, "all that can be done is to negotiate a territory proposal and a new Bosnian peace initiative." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> According to the statement, in the referendum held on August 27 and 28 more than 90 percent of the voters opposed the territorial divisions proposed by the International Contact Group. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> In his statement Krajisnik explained further that "Our rejection of the territorial divisions is only a rejection of one part of the Bosnian Peace Accord. </seg>
<seg id=5> However, the rejection in the referendum of the territorial division brings an end to the peace accord." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> When speaking of the relationship between Bosnian Serbs and Yugoslavia, Krajisnik said "the West's policy is to split up Serbs, they've been waiting for this day for a long time," but "Our goal is to unite all Serbs." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> On the same day, the foreign minister for Bosnia's "Republic of Serbia" made a statement to Agence France-Presse that "with this referendum held by Bosnian Serbs, Serbs hope that the International Contact Group will have a new proposal to take us beyond this impasse." </seg>
</p>
